JS RAFAELI: We'll have a chat.

00:38:58.590 --> 00:39:01.870
AUDIENCE: Does the political
influence from the US

00:39:01.870 --> 00:39:04.450
that you mentioned that
started this whole demise

00:39:04.450 --> 00:39:06.610
of the British System
after World War II,

00:39:06.610 --> 00:39:07.940
does that still exist today?

00:39:07.940 --> 00:39:10.480
Or is our drug policy
still influenced

00:39:10.480 --> 00:39:12.678
by what the US wants?

00:39:12.678 --> 00:39:13.678
JS RAFAELI: [INAUDIBLE].

00:39:13.678 --> 00:39:18.430
NEIL WOODS: Yeah,
well the US influence

00:39:18.430 --> 00:39:21.910
reached its pinnacle and a
fairly indelible pinnacle

00:39:21.910 --> 00:39:24.820
in 1961 with a treaty--

00:39:24.820 --> 00:39:28.520
the United Nations
Conventions on Narcotic Drugs.

00:39:28.520 --> 00:39:30.010
And that was a
treaty that everyone

00:39:30.010 --> 00:39:31.810
had to sign up to, really.

00:39:31.810 --> 00:39:34.390
They'd spent a couple of
decades winning everybody around

00:39:34.390 --> 00:39:34.983
to do that.

00:39:34.983 --> 00:39:37.400
And it's interesting that that
single treaty in the United

00:39:37.400 --> 00:39:40.790
Nations, which forces everyone
to follow the prohibition model

00:39:40.790 --> 00:39:45.520
according to the
United States doctrine,

00:39:45.520 --> 00:39:47.290
how it's described in
the United Nations.

00:39:47.290 --> 00:39:50.090
Drugs are described as evil.

00:39:50.090 --> 00:39:57.320
It's the only United Nations
treaty which uses that word.

00:39:57.320 --> 00:39:59.930
Genocide, they don't
use the word evil.

00:39:59.930 --> 00:40:02.240
So genocide's not
evil, but drugs are.

00:40:02.240 --> 00:40:04.580
So you can see that even in
the writing of the treaty

00:40:04.580 --> 00:40:07.010
that sort of moral judgment
is written into it.

00:40:07.010 --> 00:40:11.480
So each individual nation
state is actually quite limited

00:40:11.480 --> 00:40:15.500
according to international
law in how they

00:40:15.500 --> 00:40:16.690
shape their own drug policy.

00:40:16.690 --> 00:40:19.310
It actually restricts
innovation now.

00:40:19.310 --> 00:40:20.870
But that's starting
to break down.

00:40:20.870 --> 00:40:22.942
Because in 2001, Portugal--

00:40:22.942 --> 00:40:24.650
which the United
Nations said at the time

00:40:24.650 --> 00:40:26.150
they were breaching the treaty--

00:40:26.150 --> 00:40:27.620
Portugal decriminalized drugs.

00:40:27.620 --> 00:40:31.820
It's not a perfect system
because organized crime still

00:40:31.820 --> 00:40:33.290
controls the supply,
so they still

00:40:33.290 --> 00:40:35.010
have the same level
of corruption.

00:40:35.010 --> 00:40:37.280
But people don't go to
jail for using drugs.

00:40:37.280 --> 00:40:41.750
And whereas, they used to
have more deaths than us.

00:40:41.750 --> 00:40:44.845
Now, whereas, we have
50 deaths per million,

00:40:44.845 --> 00:40:46.470
they now have three
deaths per million.

00:40:46.470 --> 00:40:49.040
So you can see that a
health-based approach helps.

00:40:49.040 --> 00:40:51.380
But there are, of
course, bigger breaches

00:40:51.380 --> 00:40:54.450
of that treaty by the
United States themselves.

00:40:54.450 --> 00:40:56.510
They have several states
which legally regulated

00:40:56.510 --> 00:40:58.040
cannabis for adult use.

00:40:58.040 --> 00:40:59.465
So they've broken the treaty.

00:40:59.465 --> 00:41:01.340
Which really, so it's
the United States which

00:41:01.340 --> 00:41:02.690
has opened the floodgates.

00:41:02.690 --> 00:41:05.300
That means everything's
on the table.

00:41:05.300 --> 00:41:06.980
The rules have
already been broken.

00:41:06.980 --> 00:41:09.290
Canada has just legally
regulated cannabis

00:41:09.290 --> 00:41:11.270
for adult use right
across the whole country.

00:41:11.270 --> 00:41:13.437
So they've gone even farther
than the United States.

00:41:13.437 --> 00:41:15.320
Obviously, Uruguay
does the same.

00:41:15.320 --> 00:41:18.330
Switzerland prescribes
heroin like we used to do.

00:41:18.330 --> 00:41:20.450
And as a result, they've
cut burglaries in half

00:41:20.450 --> 00:41:22.500
and saved countless lives.

00:41:22.500 --> 00:41:26.510
So there are examples of good
drug policy which is coming--

00:41:26.510 --> 00:41:28.940
now, it's almost
like we're starting

00:41:28.940 --> 00:41:32.690
to cast off those shackles
of the United Nations

00:41:32.690 --> 00:41:35.914
single convention in 1961.

00:41:35.914 --> 00:41:39.300
AUDIENCE: There's an argument
that the privatization

00:41:39.300 --> 00:41:41.160
of the prison
systems across the US

00:41:41.160 --> 00:41:44.340
has actually resulted in
higher levels of incarceration.

00:41:44.340 --> 00:41:45.840
Is that a similar
system, you think,

00:41:45.840 --> 00:41:48.930
is now playing out in the UK
as we adopt a similar model?

00:41:48.930 --> 00:41:51.750
Do you think that's actually
one of the driving forces

00:41:51.750 --> 00:41:54.216
behind the laws not changing?

00:41:54.216 --> 00:41:56.110
JS RAFAELI: Neil, I
think you should-- yeah.

00:41:56.110 --> 00:41:58.110
NEIL WOODS: Yeah.

00:41:58.110 --> 00:42:00.600
There's a different type of
corruption in America as well.

00:42:00.600 --> 00:42:02.080
And that is like--

00:42:02.080 --> 00:42:04.470
so corporate corruption.

00:42:04.470 --> 00:42:07.680
And the influence of
both the financing

00:42:07.680 --> 00:42:10.320
behind private prisons and also,
actually, the prison officers

00:42:10.320 --> 00:42:12.810
unions put great
pressure on politicians

00:42:12.810 --> 00:42:15.790
to not change the drug laws.

00:42:15.790 --> 00:42:18.570
And the reason for that
is America has only 5%

00:42:18.570 --> 00:42:19.860
of the world's population.

00:42:19.860 --> 00:42:24.510
They have almost a quarter of
the world's prison population.

00:42:24.510 --> 00:42:28.760
One in three black
families have a male adult,

00:42:28.760 --> 00:42:30.720
a male parent in prison.

00:42:30.720 --> 00:42:32.850
I mean, this is
absolutely extraordinary.

00:42:32.850 --> 00:42:35.960
From the redeclaration of
the war on drugs from Reagan,

00:42:35.960 --> 00:42:39.000
at that time they had around
200,000 people in prison.

00:42:39.000 --> 00:42:41.475
Now they have 2.2 million.

00:42:41.475 --> 00:42:43.100
That's an incredible
increase, and it's

00:42:43.100 --> 00:42:44.930
all about the war on drugs.

00:42:44.930 --> 00:42:48.020
And it's made things worse,
because they have the highest

00:42:48.020 --> 00:42:49.920
opioid problem in the world.

00:42:49.920 --> 00:42:51.360
They have the
biggest drug deaths.

00:42:51.360 --> 00:42:52.500
It's causing carnage.

00:42:52.500 --> 00:42:54.625
You know, there is another
cause and effect there.

00:42:54.625 --> 00:42:56.000
So to answer your
question, there

00:42:56.000 --> 00:43:00.950
is a huge political influence
in lobbying in the USA,

00:43:00.950 --> 00:43:03.500
and it is one of the
many stumbling blocks

00:43:03.500 --> 00:43:05.245
to reform in the United States.

00:43:05.245 --> 00:43:06.620
But as to the
question in the UK.

00:43:06.620 --> 00:43:08.420
No, we don't have that excuse.

00:43:08.420 --> 00:43:10.550
I think our private
prisons have actually

00:43:10.550 --> 00:43:12.590
reduced in the last few years.

00:43:12.590 --> 00:43:15.010
There was one closed.

00:43:15.010 --> 00:43:17.760
I think there's only
seven, actually.

00:43:17.760 --> 00:43:20.790
And, of course, the way that
the system works in the United

00:43:20.790 --> 00:43:22.760
Kingdom, there
are limits to what

00:43:22.760 --> 00:43:24.133
financial lobbying can be done.

00:43:24.133 --> 00:43:26.300
So you're not going to have
quite the same influence

00:43:26.300 --> 00:43:29.720
on politicians--
financial influence.

00:43:29.720 --> 00:43:31.532
So we don't have the
same excuse, really.

00:43:31.532 --> 00:43:32.990
Our politicians
don't, I would say.

00:43:35.560 --> 00:43:37.550
JS RAFAELI: So can
I just jump in?

00:43:37.550 --> 00:43:39.950
There is a absolute
indelible connection

00:43:39.950 --> 00:43:45.980
between the war on drugs and not
the prison industrial complex

00:43:45.980 --> 00:43:47.300
that they have in the States.

00:43:47.300 --> 00:43:51.830
But there is a massive crisis
in UK prisons right now.

00:43:51.830 --> 00:43:56.210
And it's worth remembering that
over 50% of prisoners in the UK

00:43:56.210 --> 00:43:58.250
are there for
drug-related offenses.

00:43:58.250 --> 00:44:01.640
So you get occasional
commentators across the media--

00:44:01.640 --> 00:44:03.210
I will not mention names, but--

00:44:03.210 --> 00:44:05.210
who say, well, the war
on drugs has never really

00:44:05.210 --> 00:44:07.040
been fought in the UK.

00:44:07.040 --> 00:44:12.170
It's an absurdity, because over
50% of the prison population

00:44:12.170 --> 00:44:15.890
is there, yeah, for
drug-related offenses.

00:44:15.890 --> 00:44:19.940
There was a report
just the other day--

00:44:19.940 --> 00:44:23.630
I mean, just two days ago about
a new unit, a special unit that

00:44:23.630 --> 00:44:27.380
has been formed to combat
police officers sneaking drugs

00:44:27.380 --> 00:44:28.520
into prisons.

00:44:28.520 --> 00:44:30.842
There's a drug crisis
inside prisons.

00:44:30.842 --> 00:44:32.300
We can't keep drugs
out of prisons.

00:44:32.300 --> 00:44:35.220
How are we going to keep
them out of society?

00:44:35.220 --> 00:44:38.450
If you come from the reading
that Neil and I have done,

00:44:38.450 --> 00:44:41.750
you, say, oh, there's a new
unit to combat corruption

00:44:41.750 --> 00:44:43.130
among prison guards.

00:44:43.130 --> 00:44:46.790
I give it three weeks before
that unit is corrupted, too.

00:44:49.390 --> 00:44:53.210
So then that is the,
like you said, is--

00:44:53.210 --> 00:44:56.750
unique to drugs
prohibition policing

00:44:56.750 --> 00:44:58.610
is that creating
a market which can

00:44:58.610 --> 00:45:00.500
corrupt the institutions
which are meant

00:45:00.500 --> 00:45:02.630
to combat it on that level.

00:45:02.630 --> 00:45:06.740
And it's absolutely unique
to the war on drugs.

00:45:06.740 --> 00:45:10.230
AUDIENCE: Given America
obviously tried prohibition

00:45:10.230 --> 00:45:13.157
with alcohol, and it
failed pretty badly,

00:45:13.157 --> 00:45:15.240
do you have any insight
into why, therefore, there

00:45:15.240 --> 00:45:18.540
was such a drive to try not only
prohibition within the States

00:45:18.540 --> 00:45:20.370
but outside of the
States with drugs?

00:45:20.370 --> 00:45:22.320
Because it seems that
it's an odd lesson

00:45:22.320 --> 00:45:26.060
to take from how they tried
prohibition with alcohol.

00:45:26.060 --> 00:45:27.060
JS RAFAELI: Interesting.

00:45:27.060 --> 00:45:30.980
The prohibition
of drugs precedes

00:45:30.980 --> 00:45:32.160
prohibition of alcohol.

00:45:32.160 --> 00:45:33.860
So the Harrison
Narcotics Tax Act

00:45:33.860 --> 00:45:40.130
was 1914, which
is what made drugs

00:45:40.130 --> 00:45:44.510
we now consider illegal illegal
inside the United States.

00:45:44.510 --> 00:45:50.060
Interestingly-- this
is my geeky historian--

00:45:50.060 --> 00:45:54.020
the first American
prohibition regime

00:45:54.020 --> 00:45:55.880
wasn't instituted in
the United States.

00:45:55.880 --> 00:45:58.490
It was instituted
in the Philippines

00:45:58.490 --> 00:46:02.420
after the Spanish-American
War when America

00:46:02.420 --> 00:46:04.400
took over the
Philippines, and it

00:46:04.400 --> 00:46:10.820
was an extension of that racist
impulse and discourse in the US

00:46:10.820 --> 00:46:14.640
that, ah, well, there are
Asian people doing these drugs.

00:46:14.640 --> 00:46:16.170
We have to clamp down on it.

00:46:16.170 --> 00:46:20.960
So it was sort of when we
describe the war on drugs

00:46:20.960 --> 00:46:24.050
as a process of
American imperialism,

00:46:24.050 --> 00:46:27.710
cultural imperialism, and
just imperialist imperialism,

00:46:27.710 --> 00:46:30.470
it's actually, if you look
at the history of this

00:46:30.470 --> 00:46:33.770
and how it grew,
it's quite literal.

00:46:33.770 --> 00:46:36.080
It was literally a
process of when America

00:46:36.080 --> 00:46:38.900
became an imperial
power and had colonies

00:46:38.900 --> 00:46:42.860
beyond its own borders, it
instituted drug prohibition

00:46:42.860 --> 00:46:44.930
regimes then.

00:46:44.930 --> 00:46:47.030
What the campaigners
within the United States,

00:46:47.030 --> 00:46:49.820
they tried to institute
it on the world stage,

00:46:49.820 --> 00:46:53.568
internationally before they
banned drugs in America.

00:46:53.568 --> 00:46:55.110
And, of course, the
rest of the world

00:46:55.110 --> 00:46:57.170
went, well, we're
not banning drugs.

00:46:57.170 --> 00:46:59.960
You don't even ban
drugs inside America.

00:46:59.960 --> 00:47:01.990
And it was mainly the
British saying that.

00:47:01.990 --> 00:47:03.650
And so the Americans
went, oh, right.

00:47:03.650 --> 00:47:07.040
Well, we better prohibit
drugs in America

00:47:07.040 --> 00:47:10.080
so that we can then export
it to the rest of world.

00:47:10.080 --> 00:47:13.310
And that's the process
by which it happened.

00:47:13.310 --> 00:47:16.832
So, yeah, no lessons
were learned.

00:47:16.832 --> 00:47:18.040
NEIL WOODS: Yeah, absolutely.

00:47:18.040 --> 00:47:19.850
And another lesson
which, of course,

00:47:19.850 --> 00:47:22.070
should have been learned
from alcohol prohibition

00:47:22.070 --> 00:47:24.440
is that actually, there
are various reasons why

00:47:24.440 --> 00:47:25.380
it came to an end.

00:47:25.380 --> 00:47:28.850
But the most important
reason is the public realized

00:47:28.850 --> 00:47:32.000
just how much it was
corrupting the police.

00:47:32.000 --> 00:47:35.813
So you hear that Eliot
Ness and The Untouchables.

00:47:35.813 --> 00:47:37.730
The reason that he was
called The Untouchables

00:47:37.730 --> 00:47:38.988
because the press mocked him.

00:47:38.988 --> 00:47:40.530
Because he did an
interview and said,

00:47:40.530 --> 00:47:42.240
well, my team are untouchable.

00:47:42.240 --> 00:47:45.020
So the press had their full
front pages the next day

00:47:45.020 --> 00:47:48.680
saying, finally, we found some
cops which are untouchable.

00:47:48.680 --> 00:47:51.360
So that there's only 12 of them.

00:47:51.360 --> 00:47:53.348
And that's how he
got the nickname.

00:47:53.348 --> 00:47:55.390
And it was that knowledge
of the corruption, what

00:47:55.390 --> 00:47:57.390
it was doing to the system
which actually turned

00:47:57.390 --> 00:47:58.850
public opinion against it.

00:47:58.850 --> 00:48:01.880
Which is why it's so
important to realize

00:48:01.880 --> 00:48:03.248
just the level of corruption.

00:48:03.248 --> 00:48:04.790
And, of course, it's
really difficult

00:48:04.790 --> 00:48:07.550
to highlight the corruption
because the Home Office

00:48:07.550 --> 00:48:12.143
instructs chief constables to
maintain public confidence.

00:48:12.143 --> 00:48:13.310
Of course, that's important.

00:48:13.310 --> 00:48:15.110
If you lose confidence
in the police then

00:48:15.110 --> 00:48:18.180
the fabric of society could
break down, et cetera.

00:48:18.180 --> 00:48:20.660
Well, I've got news
for you, Home Office.

00:48:20.660 --> 00:48:22.970
The fabric of society
is breaking down,

00:48:22.970 --> 00:48:26.050
and people are losing confidence
because we're not being honest,

00:48:26.050 --> 00:48:29.010
and we're not actually dealing
with the problems that exist.

00:48:29.010 --> 00:48:31.590
So yeah, please,
please, wish more people

00:48:31.590 --> 00:48:35.366
and studied what happened
in the 1920s in America.

00:48:35.366 --> 00:48:37.970
AUDIENCE: If you had
a magic wand, what

00:48:37.970 --> 00:48:40.288
would be your first
policy, and what

00:48:40.288 --> 00:48:42.080
do you think would have
the biggest impact?

00:48:42.080 --> 00:48:43.915
NEIL WOODS: Oh,
well, that's easy.

